----------------------------------------------------------------------

              INSTALLATION!

Minimal! If you want online help then you should copy the APUNT.HELP
file into your 'T:' directory which is where AMIGAPUNT will look for
it. If it can't find it then you're given the option to select the
APUNT.HELP file via a file requester.

Alternatively you may care to dump APUNT.HELP to your printer. 

I have provided two batch files to install and/ or print 'APUNT.HELP'.
Note that you will need 'ICONX'(WB 1.3)  in your C: directory for the
batch files to work properly.


I also suggest you create a directory to which you can save rated races
for future reference.


----------------------------------------------------------------------


            THEORY & GUESSWORK.

The idea for 'AMIGAPUNT' came from an article published in a popular
punting magazine some years ago. The notion is that the factors
affecting a horse's performance and, ultimately, the result of the
race, can be given a value. The article argued that four factors were
at work:

    FACTOR                      VALUE
    -----------------------------------------------------
    
    FITNESS.    
    The general condition of the horse.         30%

    CONSISTENCY
    The 'strike rate' of wins of the
    horse.                      		30%

    WEIGHT
    If the horse carries less than the others
    than that's a bonus            		 20%

    QUALITY
    Breeding and the types of races won
    will determine the quality         		 10%


    CHAOS FACTOR
    Uncertainty                 		10%

       ------------------------------------------------------

AMIGAPUNT takes these ideas considerably further. ELEVEN factors are
identified and are given a default value. The user may change these to
suit his evaluations.

       ------------------------------------------------------   
    
            USING AMIGAPUNT

Ideally you should use a good form guide such as the 'SPORTSMAN'.
Failing that any form giving you last starts details will do. THE
AUSTRALIAN & the SYDNEY MORNING HERALD'S GOLDEN GUIDE will do nicely.

Evaluating race horses is a subjective business so I am not going to
bore you with my pet theories. However, rating systems such as
'AMIGAPUNT' will (probably, as likely as not, perhaps) show best
results if you follow a few rules:

    1)  SELECT QUALITY RACES WHICH HAVE BIG PRIZE MONEY.

    2)  AVOID RACES WHERE MORE THAN 30% OF THE STARTERS
        HAVE NO RECENT FORM.

    3)  SELECT RACES WITH SMALL FIELDS. AVOID RACES WITH
        MORE THAN 14 OR 15 STARTERS.

    4)  BE CONSISTENT IN YOUR APPROACH.


    

